5.     The Municipal Accountant to adopt the perpetual inventory system in recording the purchases of supplies and materials as provided for under Sections 114 of the NGAS Manual, Volume I;

6.  The GSO to require the different Municipal Departments/Offices to: prepare a summary of supplies and materials issued for consolidation by the GSO and submission to the Office of the Municipal Accountant as required under Section 121 of the NGAS Manual, Volume I; and conduct physical inventory of supplies and materials, by type, as required under Section 124 of the same Manual.; and

7.  The GSO and Accounting Office oversee the conduct of the inventory process regularly to ensure control, monitoring, and accounting of all inventory items and accurately report the balances as presented in the Municipality’s financial statements.

55.  The Municipality to formulate hiring plan of casuals and job orders to strengthen internal controls pertaining thereto. Department heads and officials should be able to provide a reasonable explanation on the need to hire such number of employees under contracts/job order.;

56.  The functions and duties of the contracted employees to be well-defined in their contracts and are clear, known and accepted by employees prior to the rendition of services to facilitate proper evaluation of work performed by these employees; and

57.  The HRMO to see to it that accomplishment reports should be evaluated vis-a-vis the terms/ services agreed upon in the contract by personnel of HRMO.

8.  Exhaust all means to support the balances of the above dormant accounts to identify and locate the debtors. Once identified, send demand letters for them to settle their long-outstanding accounts;

9.  If all efforts were exerted and the result of the above recommendation (1) renders futile, follow the guidelines outlined in COA Circular 2016-005 to request for the write-off of these accounts, if warranted; and

10.   Use the proper use and classification of accounts per COA Circular No. 2015-009 which prescrib.ed the Revised Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units under PPSAS.

11.  Maintain subsidiary account by year and by donor if from other sources. This is to ensure clear monitoring of funds and to properly account any unutilized amount after the five-year period. Any unutilized amount after five years should be reverted to the un-appropriated surplus of the general fund and should be made available for use to any DRRM activities and other social services after subsequent enactment by Local Sanggunian.;

12.   Reconcile the outstanding balance of Trust Liabilities-DRRM to the amounts presented in the utilization report and perform adjustments to the said account if found appropriate.; and

13.  Submit subsidiary ledger of Trust Liabilities-DRRM to MDRMO Officer every year end to monitor and evaluate the balances of the said account. Any unutilized balance of DRRM budget (except capital outlay) at year-end that is not transferred to Trust Liabilities-DRRM, shall be notified by the DRRM Officer to the Municipal Account for necessary adjustments.

14.    Instruct the Municipal Accountant to allow the office of DRRM to use the unexpended MOOE of 70% mitigation funds in Trust Liability-DRRM account and other continuing appropriations in compliance with Section 4.4 of COA Circular 2012-002. Also, restrict the unexpended 30% QRF reserved for any future calamity that might strike in the municipality. Separate the SL per year for 30% QRF and 70% QRF to account properly the unexpended funds pertaining to it.;

15.  Direct the DRRM Officer to conduct adequate planning so that programmed projects/activities under LDRRM funds be reasonably attained in the current year and to obtain optimum utilization of the available funds.; and

16.   Ensure that unexpended balance of MOOE from the 70% mitigation fund of the current year be reprogrammed in the ensuing year and the planned PPAs be incorporated to LDRRMFIP and revised AIP.

17.   Instruct the Municipal Accountant to allow the office of DRRM to use the unexpended MOOE of 70% mitigation funds in Trust Liability-DRRM account and other continuing appropriations in compliance with Section 4.4 of COA Circular 2012-002. Also, restrict the unexpended 30% QRF reserved for any future calamity that might strike in the municipality. Separate the SL per year for 30% QRF and 70% QRF to account properly the unexpended funds pertaining to it.;

18.   Direct the DRRM Officer to conduct adequate planning so that programmed projects/activities under LDRRM funds be reasonably attained in the current year and to obtain optimum utilization of the available funds.; and

19.  Ensure that unexpended balance of MOOE from the 70% mitigation fund of the current year be reprogrammed/re-appropriated in the ensuing year and the planned PPAs be incorporated to LDRRMFIP and revised AIP.

21.  Send demand letters to all concerned employees/officials with outstanding unliquidated cash advance for the immediate liquidation/settlement or refund thereof.;

22. Closely monitor the above cash advances by reviewing previous cash advances and refuse to grant cash advances to those employees with unliquidated cash advance in the books.;

23.  Upon granting cash advances, remind the officials or employees to settle/liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period as stated above.; and

24. Observe proper accounting of liquidation pertaining to prior years (i.e., use the account Prior Period Adjustment).

38.  Thoroughly review the cited programs and projects of the remaining fund of P41,200,331.02 and prioritize it to the assessed needs of the locality through the Municipal Planning and Development Council;

39.  Conduct adequate planning so that programmed projects in the AIP be reasonably attained in the current year to obtain optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund. See to it that projects that are unlikely to be implemented in the current year would not be part of the priority projects; and

40.   Ensure unexpended balance of the current year is promptly reprogrammed/re-appropriated in the ensuing year as prescribed in Sec. 322 of RA 7160.

50.   The General Services Officer to amend the Annual Procurement Plan (APP) of the municipality such that all procurement/purchases should be in accordance with an Approved Procurement Plan (APP);

51.  The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly comply with all the requirements stipulated in the New Procurement Law or R.A 9184 and its implementing guidelines pertaining to procurement keeping watch of the completeness of the supporting documents to be attached to the DV prior to submission to the Audit Team; and

52.   The Municipal Accountant to see to it that all payments for the purchase of goods should be supported with properly and filled out supporting documents before affixing her signature in Box A and exercise due diligence in the department/office acting as the internal auditor of the municipality.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to direct the Inventory and Appraisal Committee and the concerned Municipal Officials to:

Re-activate Inventory and Appraisal Committee to identify and appraise all properties whose cost cannot be reliably determined due to unavailability of financial records. Require the committee to prepare Appraisal Report and submit it to the Commission on Audit for Technical Review and Inspection;

Dutifully conduct the annual physical count of all the property, plant and equipment owned by the Municipality to establish the existence and correct the balances of PPE accounts;

Prepare promptly and completely the Report on the Physical Count of PPE as per regulation stated above;

Submit religiously the RPCPPE of the preceding year to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year; and

The GSO and the Municipal Accountant should completely maintain the prescribed Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards respectively and reconcile it with the RPCPPE to establish the correct amount of the PPE in the financial statements.
